<sn><md>## Human Settlement{.text-center}

:::.row
:::.col-12 .col-lg-6
&gt; Settlements are the result of ++interaction between people and their environment++, influenced by factors such as climate, landforms, water availability, natural resources, and socio-economic conditions.

&gt; Human settlement refers to the `organized habitation of people in a specific area`. 

It includes villages, towns, and cities where humans establish dwellings, social institutions, economic activities, and cultural practices. 

:::

:::.col-12 .col-lg-6
![fig](https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/d/dc/Flora_OR_-_aerial.jpg)
:::
:::
</md></sn><sn><md>### Characteristics{.text-center}

* `Population` – Concentration of people in a given area.
* `Shelter` – Houses, apartments, or huts for residence.
* `Infrastructure` – Roads, transport, water supply, and electricity.
* `Economic Activities` – Agriculture, industry, services, and trade.
* `Social Institutions` – Schools, hospitals, places of worship, and governance systems.
* `Cultural Identity` – Language, traditions, and customs that shape settlement life.
</md></sn><sn><md>### Types of Human Settlements{.text-center}

:::.row

:::.col-12 .col-lg-6
#### Permanency{.text-center}
* `Temporary` Settlements – Nomadic camps, seasonal huts, shifting cultivation settlements.
* `Permanent` Settlements – Villages, towns, and cities where people live continuously.
:::

:::.col-12 .col-lg-6
#### Location{.text-center}
* `Rural` Settlements – Based mainly on ++primary economic activities++ like agriculture, fishing, mining, and forestry.
* `Urban` Settlements – Focused on ++secondary and tertiary economic activities++ such as manufacturing, trade, and services.
:::

:::

#### Pattern{.text-center}
:::.row

:::.col-12 .col-lg-6
* `Dispersed` Settlements – Houses spread far apart, common in hilly or forested areas.
* `Nucleated` Settlements – Houses clustered together around resources like water bodies or fertile land.
* `Linear` Settlements – Settlements stretched along roads, rivers, or valleys.
* `Radial` Settlements – Spread out from a central point like a market or crossroad.
:::

:::.col-12 .col-lg-6
![fig](https://opentext.wsu.edu/introtohumangeography/wp-content/uploads/sites/106/2019/06/Figure-12.6.jpg)
:::

:::
</md></sn><sn><md>### Factors Influencing Human Settlements{.text-center}

:::.row
:::.col-12 .col-lg-6
#### Physical Factors{.text-center}
* Water supply (rivers, lakes, groundwater)
* Relief (plains, plateaus, mountains)
* Climate (temperature, rainfall)
* Soil fertility
* Natural resources
:::

:::.col-12 .col-lg-6
#### Cultural and Human Factors{.text-center}
* Agricultural practices
* Industrial development
* Political stability
* Historical and religious importance
* Transport and trade routes
:::
:::
</md></sn><sn><md>### Functions{.text-center}
* `Residential` Function – Providing living space for populations.
* `Economic Function` – Centers of agriculture, industry, trade, and services.
* `Administrative Function` – Capitals and towns with government institutions.
* `Cultural Function` – Places of heritage, tradition, and learning.
* `Defense Function` – Fortified cities and strategic locations.
</md></sn><sn><md>### Evolution{.text-center}
* `Prehistoric Settlements` – Caves, rock shelters, and nomadic camps.
* `Agricultural Villages` – Emerged with the Neolithic Revolution.
* `Medieval Towns` – Grew around trade routes, forts, and religious centers.
* `Modern Cities` – Industrial and service-oriented with advanced infrastructure.
* `Mega Cities &amp; Smart Cities` – Highly urbanized with global connectivity and technology-based services.
</md></sn><sn><md>### Importance{.text-center}
* Helps understand human-environment interaction.
* Aids in urban and rural planning.
* Guides sustainable development policies.
* Provides insight into cultural evolution and social organization.
</md></sn><sn><md>### Conclusion

Human settlement is a dynamic phenomenon shaped by both natural and cultural factors. From small rural villages to global mega cities, settlements reflect human adaptation, economic growth, and cultural expression. Understanding their patterns, evolution, and functions is essential for effective planning, resource management, and building sustainable futures.
